Hardwired Genome Overview

Hardwired Genome is a utility for analyzing protein-protein interactions.

Opening the Hardwired Genome

In the MATLAB Command Window, type
hwg

These are the default settings when the software is launched. The entire protein-coding genome is used. The network plot is partitioned by chromosome.
UBA52 is the most interactive protein in the entire genome. The network is 99.69% sparse and contains 18,339 proteins. A brief description about gene groups:
  • G1 = Master Regulators
  • G2 = Transcription Factors
  • G3 = Proteins

Selecting a Subnetwork of Interest

  1. Select 'Cell Cycle - iReprogram' from the Network Dropdown
  2. Select Eigenvector from the Centrality Radiobuttons
The 'Cell Cycle - iReprogram' network is loaded into the plot window with the primary gene groups labeled on the axes.
CDK2 has the highest Eigenvector centrality of all proteins in the network.

Loading External RNA-Seq Data

  1. Select External from the 'Cell Type' Dropdown
  2. Select proliferative_fibroblast from the Dialog
  3. Set the 'Expression Threshold' to a value of 6
  4. Select G1 from the 'Gene Group' Radiobuttons
The active interactions for a proliferative fibroblast are highlighted in blue. These interactions are used in the network centrality computations.
The centrality table is filtered to only include master regulators. Note that E2F1 is not present when using a quiescent fibroblast.

Notes on External RNA-Seq Data

  • Proliferative and quiescent fibroblast data used in this example was collected from the Sequence Read Archive
  • The software requires that processed RNA-Seq data is stored in the following tab-delimited text format
  • Data stored in the above format may be loaded into the software with a single mouse-click
